---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { partyColour } from "../../../lib/predictions";
import { shortPartyLabel } from "../../../lib/siteData";
import { readFileSync } from "node:fs";
import path from "node:path";

const data = JSON.parse(
  readFileSync(
    path.join(process.cwd(), "data/predictions/historical/demographic-indicator-backtest.json"),
    "utf8",
  ),
);

const PARTIES = ["Reform UK", "Labour", "Conservative", "Liberal Democrats", "Green Party"];
const PREDICTORS = ["imd", "white_british", "asian", "no_quals", "degree", "retired"];

function fmtR(r: number): string {
  if (r == null) return "—";
  return (r >= 0 ? "+" : "") + r.toFixed(3);
}

function fmtPct(x: number, d = 1): string {
  return (x * 100).toFixed(d) + "%";
}

function strength(r: number): string {
  const a = Math.abs(r);
  if (a > 0.8) return "very strong";
  if (a > 0.6) return "strong";
  if (a > 0.4) return "moderate";
  if (a > 0.2) return "weak";
  return "near-zero";
}

const perParty = data.per_party as Record<string, any>;
const predictive = data.predictive_backtest_2025_to_2026 as Record<string, any>;
const bestIndicator = data.best_indicator_per_party as Record<string, any>;
const n2025 = data.summary.n_councils_2025;
const n2026 = data.summary.n_councils_2026;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Demographic indicators — backtest 2025 → 2026"
  description={`Backtest of the demographic theories of British council voting against the 2026 local elections (n=${n2026} councils). Reform's degree-share signal is the most stable relationship; Labour's coalition reshuffled hard between 2025 and 2026; Conservatives have lost demographic predictability.`}
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Past results · Indicator backtest</p>
    <h1>What predicts vote share — and does it hold up across elections?</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      We ran the same demographic regression on the <strong>1 May 2025</strong>
      county council elections (n={n2025} councils) and the <strong>1 May 2026</strong>
      local elections (n={n2026} councils) for each major party. The headline:
      <strong>Reform UK's correlation with degree-holder share (r ≈ −0.85) is
      the single most stable, lawful demographic relationship in modern English
      local elections.</strong> Other parties' coefficients moved meaningfully
      between the two years — diagnostic of real coalitional reshuffling, not noise.
    </p>
    <p class="meta-row">
      Predictors: IMD decile, White British %, Asian %, no-qualifications %,
      degree %, retired % · Source: DC historic results + Census 2021 +
      IMD 2019 + LA ethnic projections.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <p class="eyebrow">Per-party best single indicator</p>
      <h2>One number per party — what to look at first</h2>
    </div>
    <p>
      Across the much larger 2026 panel (n={n2026}), the strongest single demographic
      predictor of each party's council-level vote share:
    </p>
    <table class="seat-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Party</th><th>Best predictor</th><th class="num">Pearson r</th><th>Direction</th><th>Strength</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        {PARTIES.map((p) => {
          const b = bestIndicator[p];
          if (!b) return null;
          return (
            <tr>
              <td><span class="party-pill" style={`background:${partyColour(p)}`}></span> {shortPartyLabel(p)}</td>
              <td>{b.predictor.replace(/_/g, " ")}</td>
              <td class="num">{fmtR(b.pearson_r)}</td>
              <td>{b.direction}</td>
              <td>{strength(b.pearson_r)}</td>
            </tr>
          );
        })}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      Reform's −0.85 with degree-share is the strongest in the set. Labour and
      the Conservatives now share IMD as their primary axis (negative for Labour,
      positive for the Conservatives), confirming the partial re-emergence of a
      traditional class divide on local government issues. Greens are best
      predicted by their younger-electorate signature.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <p class="eyebrow">Backtest A — coefficient stability 2025 → 2026</p>
      <h2>Which correlations held up, and which moved?</h2>
    </div>
    <p>
      Same predictor, different election. Where the correlation is stable across
      both years, the demographic relationship is real and lawful. Where it moved
      meaningfully, the underlying coalition shifted.
    </p>
    <table class="seat-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Party</th>
          <th>Predictor</th>
          <th class="num">2025 r (n={n2025})</th>
          <th class="num">2026 r (n={n2026})</th>
          <th class="num">Stability</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {PARTIES.map((p) => {
          const r25 = perParty[p].regression_2025?.single_predictor_pearson || {};
          const r26 = perParty[p].regression_2026?.single_predictor_pearson || {};
          return PREDICTORS.map((pred, i) => {
            const v25 = r25[pred];
            const v26 = r26[pred];
            const delta = (v25 != null && v26 != null) ? Math.abs(v25 - v26) : null;
            const stab = delta == null ? "—" : delta < 0.1 ? "stable" : delta < 0.3 ? "moderate shift" : "large shift";
            return (
              <tr>
                {i === 0 ? <td rowspan={PREDICTORS.length}><strong><span class="party-pill" style={`background:${partyColour(p)}`}></span> {shortPartyLabel(p)}</strong></td> : null}
                <td>{pred.replace(/_/g, " ")}</td>
                <td class="num">{fmtR(v25)}</td>
                <td class="num">{fmtR(v26)}</td>
                <td class="num">
                  <span class={delta == null ? "swing-flat" : delta < 0.1 ? "swing-flat" : delta < 0.3 ? "swing-down" : "swing-down"}>
                    {stab}
                  </span>
                </td>
              </tr>
            );
          });
        })}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      <strong>Reform UK degree-share is the most stable correlation in the set</strong>
      (−0.896 → −0.853, delta 0.04). Reform's no-quals correlation weakened (+0.91 → +0.59)
      as its vote broadened beyond the no-quals base; its white-British and retired
      correlations both strengthened materially as the vote consolidated in
      older White British areas.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Labour underwent the largest coalitional shift.</strong> Its no-quals
      correlation collapsed (+0.78 → +0.20), its degree correlation flipped sign
      (−0.56 → +0.18), and its IMD correlation strengthened (−0.29 → −0.64). Labour
      in 2026 is now "younger graduates in more-deprived urban areas" rather than
      the cross-class coalition it was in 2025. The R² of the same regression also
      fell (0.77 → 0.59) — Labour's vote is now less demographically predictable.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Conservatives have minimal demographic predictability either year</strong>
      (R² ≈ 0.40 both years) — their vote depends much more on local incumbency,
      candidate quality, and tactical voting than on any of these axes. The one
      meaningful shift is on IMD: it flipped from near-zero (−0.025) in 2025 to
      strongly positive (+0.50) in 2026, consistent with the Conservatives becoming
      "the wealthy who haven't gone Reform yet".
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <p class="eyebrow">Backtest B — predictive accuracy</p>
      <h2>Train on 2025 coefficients, predict 2026 vote share</h2>
    </div>
    <p>
      The hardest test: take each party's 2025-trained regression coefficients,
      apply them to every 2026 council's demographics, and compare predicted vs
      actual vote share. Mean Absolute Error in percentage points (lower = better):
    </p>
    <table class="seat-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Party</th>
          <th class="num">2025 mean share</th>
          <th class="num">2026 mean share</th>
          <th class="num">MAE (pp)</th>
          <th class="num">RMSE (pp)</th>
          <th class="num">Pearson r (pred vs actual)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {PARTIES.map((p) => {
          const r25 = perParty[p].regression_2025;
          const r26 = perParty[p].regression_2026;
          const pred = predictive[p];
          if (!pred) return null;
          return (
            <tr>
              <td><span class="party-pill" style={`background:${partyColour(p)}`}></span> {shortPartyLabel(p)}</td>
              <td class="num">{r25 ? fmtPct(r25.mean_share) : "—"}</td>
              <td class="num">{r26 ? fmtPct(r26.mean_share) : "—"}</td>
              <td class="num">{pred.mae_pp.toFixed(2)}pp</td>
              <td class="num">{pred.rmse_pp.toFixed(2)}pp</td>
              <td class="num">{fmtR(pred.correlation)}</td>
            </tr>
          );
        })}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      <strong>Reform UK has the strongest predictive correlation</strong>
      (r=+0.676 between predicted and actual 2026 vote share) on an 8.4pp MAE.
      The demographic-only model captures the relative ranking of councils
      better for Reform than for any other party, even though absolute levels
      shifted modestly as Reform's national vote broadened.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Conservatives have the worst predictive accuracy</strong>
      (MAE 11.5pp, r=+0.26) — using 2025 coefficients massively over-predicts
      Conservative vote in 2026 in places where the demographic profile looked
      "Tory" on paper but Reform actually swept. This is direct quantitative
      evidence of the Conservative-to-Reform vote shift.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Liberal Democrats have a large MAE (12.2pp) but decent correlation
      (r=+0.53)</strong> — the demographic ranking is right but the absolute
      levels rose in 2026 (LDs gained vote share generally). A 2026-trained
      model would do better in level, even if 2025-trained captures the
      cross-council ranking.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <p class="eyebrow">Per-party demographic signature</p>
      <h2>What each party looks like on the demographics</h2>
    </div>
    {PARTIES.map((p) => {
      const r25 = perParty[p].regression_2025;
      const r26 = perParty[p].regression_2026;
      return (
        <div style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
          <h3 style="margin-top:1rem;">
            <span class="party-pill" style={`background:${partyColour(p)}`}></span> {shortPartyLabel(p)}
          </h3>
          <p>
            <strong>2025 R² = {r25?.r_squared ?? "—"} · 2026 R² = {r26?.r_squared ?? "—"}</strong>
            {r25 && r26 ? (
              <span> · 2025 mean vote {fmtPct(r25.mean_share)} → 2026 mean vote {fmtPct(r26.mean_share)}</span>
            ) : null}
          </p>
          <table class="seat-table">
            <thead><tr><th>Predictor</th><th class="num">2025 r</th><th class="num">2026 r</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              {PREDICTORS.map((pred) => (
                <tr>
                  <td>{pred.replace(/_/g, " ")}</td>
                  <td class="num">{fmtR(r25?.single_predictor_pearson?.[pred])}</td>
                  <td class="num">{fmtR(r26?.single_predictor_pearson?.[pred])}</td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      );
    })}
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <p class="eyebrow">Headline conclusions</p>
      <h2>What we can take to the bank</h2>
    </div>
    <ol class="numbered-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Reform UK's degree-share correlation (r ≈ −0.85) is the most
        stable lawful relationship in modern English local elections.</strong>
        It held within 0.04 points across both years on totally different
        samples (n=24 county councils in 2025 vs n=136 mixed local elections
        in 2026). Graduates repel Reform, full stop.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Reform's vote broadened in 2026 beyond its no-quals base.</strong>
        The no-quals correlation weakened (+0.91 → +0.59) while the white-British
        (+0.41 → +0.71) and retired-share (+0.28 → +0.69) correlations both
        strengthened. The 2026 Reform vote is more "older, whiter, retired"
        than "low-qualifications" specifically.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Labour's coalition has reshuffled hard.</strong> The Labour
        coefficient pattern looks nothing like 2025: no-quals dropped from
        +0.78 to +0.20, degree flipped from −0.56 to +0.18, retired from
        −0.11 to −0.56. Labour 2026 is "younger graduates in more-deprived
        urban areas" — fundamentally a different coalition. Labour's R²
        also dropped (0.77 → 0.59) — its vote is now less demographically
        predictable.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Conservatives have no clear demographic signature</strong>
        (R² ≈ 0.40 both years). Their vote is now driven more by local
        incumbency, candidate quality, and tactical voting than by any
        demographic axis. Their training-on-2025 prediction accuracy for 2026
        is the worst of all parties (MAE 11.5pp, r=0.26) — direct evidence
        of the Conservative-to-Reform shift.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>IMD is the Labour-Conservative axis; degree is the
        Reform-everything-else axis.</strong> The two axes are roughly
        independent. Both matter, but for different parties. A national
        model that uses only IMD or only degree will systematically misread
        either Labour or Reform.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>For ward-level Reform forecasting, no-quals % is the most
        practical proxy</strong> (degree % is nearly perfectly anti-correlated;
        either works). At LA / council level, the choice is irrelevant — both
        deliver the same ranking. The implementation question is which is
        available in the ward demographic file (both are, but no-quals
        intuitively maps to the Reform coalition better in narrative terms).
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <details class="section method-details">
    <summary>Methodology</summary>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>Sample.</strong> 1 May 2025: 24 councils (11 unitaries + 14 county councils). 1 May 2026: 136 councils (all tier-local contests where a slug → LAD24 mapping resolves).</li>
      <li><strong>Demographics.</strong> Population-weighted aggregation of constituent LAD24 demographics — IMD 2019 (mean of LSOA deciles), 2026 ethnic projections (linear interpolation between Census 2021 + 2031 ONS midpoint), Census 2021 (TS021/030/054/066/067/004) aggregated to LAD by resident-population weight.</li>
      <li><strong>Regression.</strong> OLS on the council panel. Predictors: intercept + IMD + white_british % + asian % + no_quals % + degree %. R², single-predictor Pearson correlations, and coefficient stability across years reported.</li>
      <li><strong>Predictive backtest.</strong> 2025 fitted coefficients applied to every 2026 council's demographics; predicted vote share compared to actual; MAE, RMSE, and Pearson r reported per party.</li>
      <li><strong>Caveats.</strong> County-council aggregation for 2-tier shires uses average district demographics weighted by ward-level resident totals; this approximates a true county-wide average but treats districts as equal-weight inside each county.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted-row">
      Raw data: <a href="https://github.com/tompickup23/ukelections/blob/main/data/predictions/historical/demographic-indicator-backtest.json">demographic-indicator-backtest.json</a>
    </p>
  </details>
</BaseLayout>
